Thursday September 12th 2013 1:45 am -04:00,Jenniferyes 0+1 is 1 that is the point of that part and the reason to add 1 is to use that as the index to start searching again.  if you start at the same point that the first finds results you will find the same first match but if you just step it by1 then it will skip that index (and the first result) and look for the next occurrence.a.find(hello1) a = hello hello helloa.find(hello)  <--- finds the first helloa.find(hello)+1 <--- is the index of the first hello + 1 a.find(hello1) <-- this will start looking at index 1 for hello since the first hello start at 0 it will not find the first hello so it will keep looking and find the second hello.  so if you combined a .find(string start_index) and a .find() youcan find the second hello.  I hope this helps  , Resolved,7
