Monday September 23rd 2013 11:45 pm -04:00,def shift_left(L):        (list) -> NoneType        Shift each item in L one position to the left and shift the first item to    the last position.        Precondition: len(L) >= 1        >>> shift_left([a b c d])            first_item = L[0]        for i in range(len(L) - 1):        L[i] = L[i + 1]        L[-1] = first_itemLets walk over this codeyou should already know what this does so we can skip the explanation def shift_left(L):     (list) -> NoneType        Shift each item in L one position to the left and shift the first item to    the last position.        Precondition: len(L) >= 1        >>> shift_left([a b c d])    this line takes the first element of the list and places it in a temporary place holder because we are going to overwrite index 0 in the next 2 steps so if we want to still use this we need to copy it somewhere.    first_item = L[0]this line starts our loop  it will include the numbers 0 to the length of list L - 1the reason for - 1 is because on the next line we will be using indexes and we will add 1 to an index to get the next index    for i in range(len(L) - 1):this line is the reason for len(L) - 1the first part takes L[i] and makes that hold the value of what ever is at L[i + 1] and we do it for every thing in the listthe item at index 1 is moved to index 0 the item at index 2 is moved to index 1 etc.......if we did not -1 in the range it would give you an index error on the last index of the list.if L = [1234]and i = 3 the line would represent L[3] = L[3 + 1]but there is not an index 4 (3+1=4) so python will give you an error and the program would stopso we stop it early and dont change the last index from inside the loop        L[i] = L[i + 1]and the last thing we do is take what we had saved in our temporary variable and put it at in the last indexsince we did not change it in the loop    L[-1] = first_item, Resolved,3
