he grader because you did not read all the columns and you might return False if the word is in one of the columns you did not readnow lets look at Jamess example boards again and see if we can find the information to fix thisthe square board is 4 rows by 4 columnswide is3 rows by 4 columnstall is 6 rows by 4 columnsokay I see a pattern  the length of a row is equal to the number of columnsif a row has 4 letters in it then that means that it will have 4 columnsif a row has 9 letters in it then that means that it will have 9 columnsevery board also has exactly 1 thing in common they all have a first roweven a 1 row by 200 column board has a first rowso that means that we now know that the length of the first row is equal to the number of columns on the boardlets go back to the for loopfor column_index in range(len(board)):so to make column_index count the columns and not the rows we will need to make a small change in the range statementright now we get the length of the board which is equal to the number of rows len(board)all we need to do is change what we get the length of instead of the len(board) we need to get the length of row 0and to do that we use indexing so board[0] because the first row is index 0 and then we use that in our len() that goes in our range() range(len(board[0]))so make the change and then like I showed you above trace this by hand and see what happens after that run it in idle or the visualizer to make sure you are getting the right answers  , Resolved,8
